Here's the migrated code and the key pitfalls:

## Migrated ASP.NET Core (.NET 8) Code

```csharp
public class ReportController : Controller
{
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult ExportReport()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();
        var bytes = System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data);
        return File(bytes, "text/csv", "report.csv");
    }

    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult RedirectAfterProcess()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            return RedirectToAction("Index", "Login"); // or Redirect("/login")
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

### 1. `Response.End()` / `Response.Redirect(..., true)` → gone
These called `Thread.Abort()` internally, which no longer exists in .NET Core. The entire pattern of imperatively writing to the response is replaced by **returning `IActionResult`**. Never catch `ThreadAbortException` — it doesn't happen.

### 2. `Response.Write()` / `Response.Clear()` → `return File(...)`
Don't manually manipulate `HttpResponse`. Use built-in results:
| Old | New |
|---|---|
| `Response.Write(data)` | `return Content(data, "text/plain")` |
| `Response.BinaryWrite(bytes)` | `return File(bytes, mimeType, fileName)` |
| `Response.AddHeader(...)` | Handled by `File()` / `Content()` automatically |

### 3. `Response.Redirect()` returns void → must `return`
In Web Forms, `Redirect(..., true)` aborted execution so code after it never ran. In Core, `Redirect()` returns a `RedirectResult` — **you must return it**, or execution continues and the framework may throw "Response already started."

```csharp
// BUG — redirect is ignored, execution continues:
Redirect("/login");
DoMoreWork(); // still runs!

// CORRECT:
return Redirect("/login");
```

### 4. Null-safety on `User.Identity`
`User.Identity` can be `null` in ASP.NET Core if no authentication middleware is configured. Use `User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? false`.

### 5. Event handlers → Action methods with routing
Web Forms `btnExport_Click` postback handlers become controller actions with explicit `[HttpPost]`/`[HttpGet]` attributes and route templates. Wire up forms accordingly:

```html
<!-- Old Web Forms -->
<asp:Button ID="btnExport" runat="server" OnClick="btnExport_Click" />

<!-- New Razor/MVC -->
<form asp-action="ExportReport" method="post">
    <button type="submit">Export</button>
</form>
```

### 6. Auth enforcement — use middleware, not manual checks
Replace hand-rolled auth checks with the `[Authorize]` attribute:

```csharp
[Authorize]
[HttpPost]
public IActionResult RedirectAfterProcess()
{
    // No manual IsAuthenticated check needed —
    // unauthenticated users are redirected automatically
    // via Program.cs configuration:
    //   builder.Services.AddAuthentication(...)
    //       .AddCookie(o => o.LoginPath = "/login");
    ProcessRequest();
    return Redirect("/success");
}
```

### Summary of mental model shift

| ASP.NET Framework | ASP.NET Core |
|---|---|
| Imperatively write to `Response` | Return an `IActionResult` |
| `Thread.Abort` ends execution | You control flow with `return` |
| Catch `ThreadAbortException` | Delete those catch blocks |
| Event-driven postbacks | Routed action methods |
| Manual auth checks | `[Authorize]` + middleware |
